        <mj-image src="https://media.whatcounts.com/hcn/layout_images/BirdDivider_02D.png" width="350px" alt="horizontal rule"></mj-image>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <!--divider end-->
    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text mj-class="body-text">
          <p><em>High Country News&rsquo;</em> Kylie Mohr accompanied scientists in Montana&rsquo;s mountains in search of &hellip;  glacial blood? Yes, that&rsquo;s one name given to algal blooms on snow, which has a pink hue. The algae reduces the snow&rsquo;s albedo &mdash; or reflectivity &mdash; thereby causing it to absorb more heat from the sun and melt more quickly. Mohr <a href="https://www.hcn.org/issues/54.12/north-water-pink-snow-is-a-red-flag-for-the-wests-water" target="_blank" rel="noopener">tells a fascinating story</a> about how scientists hope to learn more about the algae&rsquo;s role as the climate changes. | <strong><em>High Country News</em></strong></p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
